notes.text: This is the trouble with sleeping without Control-IQ on. BG had only just started to rise when I went to bed and I gave myself a correction bolus but I didn’t know it would keep rising during my sleep. I think it must have risen due to a slow-acting dinner rather than a basal rate that was too low since the previous night when I was fasting my BG didn’t go high and I had to suspend my basal to prevent going low. And if the slow-acting meal was the cause the trouble is my pump has a frustrating maximum of 2 hours for extended boluses.

I’ve been going high lately during my gym session which I suspect could be from my pre-workout drink that spikes my BG. So today I tried waiting till the start of my workout before I started having it instead of having it before my workout. It seems that timing change caused me to go hypo during my workout. So I’m not sure what the perfect timing is yet.

Although I’m quite happy with my BG through the night here, the alarms needed to control my BG are a problem. I have my low alarm set to 4.6 so that if I’m heading low during my sleep I have the chance to suspend my insulin before it’s too late, and repeat alarms every 30 minutes. So I was getting very frequent alarms through the night even though I’m happy hovering below 4.6. I really don’t want to have any alarms during my sleep on a normal basis let alone every 30 minutes. So I don’t know what to do.

Again, I’m getting annoying low Dexcom alerts like every 30 minutes. By turning Control-IQ off I love that I can actually stay this close to 4mmol/L but I’d be afraid of turning off my low alert and it will drive me crazy if I keep having to listen to the alerts this often and interrupt what I’m doing in order to acknowledge the alert in the Dexcom app or else it will keep bugging me even more often. And for some reason even after I acknowledge the alert in the Dexcom app, only minutes later it alerts me again.

How does a salad like this spike my BG??
4:24pm. BG 3.9. Started salad. 
4:46pm Apple. 
5:00pm BG 6.2. 
Given that CGM readings are 15(?) mins behind real BG this spike couldn’t have been from the apple so it was apparently from the salad. I’ve noticed my salads surprisingly raise my BG but I’m afraid of bolusing too much for my salads then going hypo because when I was first diagnosed I was told not to give myself insulin for meals like salad. I did bolus my usual insulin/carb ratio for my salad, just extended over an hour because it takes time to eat and it’s not supposed to spike my BG. Do I need to change my mentality and stop thinking of salads as something that shouldn’t need insulin?

1. Before I went to sleep I changed my Dexcom low alarm from 4.6 to 4.3 in the hope of getting a night’s sleep without alarms. Apparently that and/or that I managed to sleep through my annoying and loud alarms caused me to go hypo.

2. It appears as though my basal rate is set too high lately as my BG graph goes down from just basal. But I recently tried a higher basal rate, attempting to set it so that my BG line would go straight when only on basal but found that I stayed too high during the night and woke up high, because even if I had a perfectly level BG line on just basal, getting it to my target depended on perfect bolusing before sleep, and I found I repeatedly had to do correction boluses. 
Whereas with this method of erring on a basal rate that is more than my real basal need, I’ve found as long as I put up with annoying frequent BG alarms, I can maintain my BG hovering just above 4 by regularly suspending my basal.
I ate a papaya around 10am which I thought I logged but it’s not showing here.

This is an example of what I find difficult - when I had my salad I didn’t know for sure that I’d be having a papaya afterwards, so I wouldn’t have wanted to pre-bolus for the papaya and then be forced to eat it in order to not have a hypo. And now my BG is 14.5 and I don’t know what to do differently to prevent this scenario from happening again. I feel like I’ve never got the hang of pre-bolusing because I find it so impractical.

I knew having fruit when my BG hadn’t yet recovered from the papaya spike wasn’t going to help my BG but it’s again a matter of needing a practical solution because pre-bolusing would have felt impractical in this scenario. I was working on this app and to pre-bolus while I’m programming would be highly frustrating because when programming things often take an unknown amount of time to solve and I don’t want to have to stop what I’m working on in order to eat because I pre-bolused. And when I finished what I was working on I didn’t want to just wait around before eating because I wanted to go for my walk before it was too late. So I expected the high BG that followed, although I’m not sure what caused the hypo. That spike followed by the hypo is what was happening before I stopped using Control-IQ and hasn’t been happening so much since I’ve been in manual mode. I wish I understood what I did wrong so I could have confidence in preventing it happening again.
Am I a strange exception to the “insulin lasts 2 hours” principle? My 2:45pm bolus seems to be lasting many hours to cause this long-lasting hypo this long afterwards.

I need a system for unfinished meals. Something about my cooked veggie dinner was making me feel sick so I didn’t finish it. I often don’t finish meals and it creates the problem of messing up my calculations both for the unfinished meals and for the next day when I eat the remainder of the meal.
Started eating the dinner I logged last night that I didn’t finish
Didn’t quite finish the cooked veggie meal. Finished next day just before the first logged food.
I tried putting my Dexcom alarm on vibrate last night, and my phone ran out of battery last night, hence the high BG through my sleep.

Since I’m finding it too hard to control my BG during my sleep without Control-IQ and without frequent Dexcom alarms, I’m experimenting this morning with turning Control-IQ back on but seeing if I can manipulate it to keep me below its target 6.1 by by giving it an aggressive correction factor of 2.

The split peas seemed to create this big BG spike. And perhaps with some help from my pre-workout drink I had without any workout, although I did bolus for it. I’ve only just discovered splits peas so I’m not familiar with how they affect my BG yet. But I thought legumes were supposed to be a great choice for BG and slow-acting, so I thought having a salad with legumes would reward me with good blood sugar and I didn’t expect this rapid big spike. I boluses my usual ratio and thought it might be too much insulin if the split peas were slow-acting but it seems my usual ratio wasn’t enough for the split peas.

Here is Control-IQ fighting me. I gave myself a correction bolus which worked briefly but now I’m above 8 because Control-IQ lowered my basal for 2 hours. This is even with my experiment with the correction factor set at 1:1 for the Control-IQ settings in the hope that that would make it keep me below its target 6.1 mmol/L. I think the 9.6 spike at 3:40am was also due to Control-IQ lowering my basal for 2 hours. I have felt like Control-IQ is working against me time and time again, but without it my Dexcom alarms are too much for me - at least during my sleep.
I ate my meal too slowly because the Instant Pot makes my food too hot to eat, so I think that played a part in the short hypo.
Turned Control-IQ on.
Started the leftovers from dinner a couple of nights ago. Wasn’t much.
I just changed my infusion site and noticed my cannula looked kinked and the site might have ripped out somewhat which could explain my high BG.
Trying another experiment now, setting my basal rate at 2u/hr while Control-IQ is on, to see if that gets my BG lower. Correction Factor is set at 2.5.
Starting last night’s dinner leftovers

I’m celebrating this hypo because it means I have successfully hacked Control-IQ to bring me lower than its target 6.1. 
My settings to do this were basal rate 1.5u/hr (much higher than my real basal rate) and correction factor 2.5 (again, more aggressive than my real correction factor). Adjusting to basal rate 1.2u/hr now because those settings were too strong.

I’m wondering if I was wrong about coffee not raising my BG noticeably because even with Control-IQ giving me a much higher basal rate than my usual basal I’m still above 6. It’s possible that since I haven’t had coffee very often and in the past I’ve had Control-IQ on, Control-IQ has made me unaware of coffee spiking me because it just increases my basal.
Normally I’ve been liking to time my walks during my fasts but today and I think on my last walk I’ve timed my walk soon after breakfast in order to help control my post breakfast spike.

Another example of why I fear pre-bolusing. I was worried when I bolused that this hypo might happen but I’m trying to correct my ongoing post-meal spikes and it seems I am over-correcting. I poured 2 cups of water on my cooked meal to prevent a repeat scenario of the hypo from 26/7 but tonight my dinner took an unexpectedly long time to cook which meant I bolused too early, apparently. It was about 20 minutes before my meal. I feel like I’ve never got the hang of pre-bolusing and it keeps on creating stressful scenarios and it ruins the enjoyment of my meal when I’ve got a numb hypo mouth and have to rush eating to catch up to the insulin.

Tonight and last night I didn’t spike after dinner like I often do. But why? Need to analyse the difference. Was it the difference between pinto beans and French lentils vs split peas? Low GI fruit vs higher GI? The tablespoon of chia seeds I had earlier in the day? Or was it the ginger I added to my dinner? I’m not in the habit of logging every single spice I eat because of how tedious that would be and I consider them negligible calories and carbs but do they affect BG enough to be worth the effort to log?
Forgot to bolus when I started my salad. But again, it seems odd that raw veggies would raise my BG like this.

Need to figure out what caused this night of long hypo. Two Nudie juices is rare for me to need. I don’t think Congrol-IQ is to blame because it looked like it had my insulin suspended for most of the time and low for the rest of the time.
I accidentally must have left my pump profile on my Control-IQ settings when I turned Control-IQ off, so I was receiving 1.2u/hr while I was workout out when I thought I was receiving only .43u/hr.

It seems amazing that even with bolusing 1.74 units for my salad - using the same insulin to carb ratio that I do for everything else - I’m still shooting up at a rate of 7.4 mmol/L per hour when I’ve just finished my salad. I was at 4.4 when I started eating my salad. And 7 minutes after finishing I’m now 7.8 shooting up at 8.6 mmol/L / hour. 11 mins after finishing I’m 8.8 shooting up at 11 mmol/L/hr without eating anything other than my salad
Started eating last night’s leftovers now

About to do an experiment - having my salad when I haven’t had any pre-workout drink or coffee to see if the salad still spikes me. BG was 5.2 when I started my salad. And 6.2 going up at 2 mmol/L/hr at 4:45pm soon after I finished. Given the 15 minute delay for CGM readings to reflect actual BG (or is it less than 15 mins lag?), and I started my apple at 4:56pm, that means even the 8.5 BG at 5:10 pm shouldn’t be affected by the apple yet, so it seems once again my salad has caused a spike, and this time without any caffeine to affect the results.

I thought I had Control-IQ turned off but I didn’t. So I thought I was getting .43u/hr tonight when I was actually getting much more because Control-IQ saw I was high. So I’ve just suspended my insulin to try and make up for that.
Then I fell asleep with my insulin suspended so I went high.

I had my pre-workout drink just before my workout without bolusing. I only suspended my insulin for just over 30 mins and my gym session was almost 3 hours. Amazingly I still finished with BG 11.2 so I had 2.06u correction bolus after my workout. It appears the drink kept raising my BG for 3 hours.
Bolusing an extra 2 units here in an attempt to figure out what it is I need to do to prevent my spike after my salad.

I don’t understand why I’m having this much trouble with high BG on a day I spent almost 3 hours at the gym. When I used to play tennis I would have trouble going hypo during and after tennis. I don’t know why the gym isn’t having the same effect. It’s not like I’m doing things at a hard enough intensity that I would expect it to elevate my BG instead of lower it. Am I wrong? Does it only take a bit of strength training to create a spike in BG and for this long afterwards??
My site was 3 days old at 10am this morning so maybe that has something to do with it but in the past I seem to be able to get away with changing it every 3.5 days. 
I’ve changed my site now to eliminate that potential cause and I’m wondering if it was another case of a bent cannula or if the site had come out. 
And now I will have no idea how much insulin I will need for dinner because I don’t know if what I gave myself before I changed my site worked.

Today I tried pre-bolusing for my salad before I even started making it. It was 37 mins before I started eating it. I had to stop eating my salad and eat my apple because I was hypo eating my salad. And I still went high anyway.

My instant pot finished cooking so I bolused for my dinner then when I opened the lid found it hadn’t cooked my dinner so I stopped my bolus in progress but it had already delivered 3.23 units. So many things that can go wrong that mess up my BG!!

But I was actually already hypo not because of that but because once again my salad/apple breakfast had spiked me, and now I’m low from my correction bolus.

Control-IQ was on for a while after the coffee then I suspended my insulin at 10:38am before my walk till 11:44am then switched to my .43u/hr manual basal. Amazing the difference between coffee and the pre-workout drink - normally I feel under control of my BG when I’m walking while fasting and I don’t go hypo. But today I had to stop my walk because I went hypo which I am confident is because I had coffee instead of the pre-workout drink. I wonder what causes the difference??
Started eating the leftovers from last night but it wasn’t much.

Trying changing to carb ratio of 15 instead of 20. The leftovers from last night add an unknown amount of carbs to the experiment though. I just bolused 1 unit for that. I also tried not having any fruit for breakfast to see if I could not spike today, so I had a split pea and veggie breakfast. I was still spiking soon after and I was still hungry. The first part of breakfast I’d bolused at the start of my meal so this time I did another bolus at a ratio of 15 and not only that, waited to eat the next part.

Notice how many more calories I consumed having a legume and cooked veggie breakfast vs my salad and apple breakfast (like 4 times as many calories?!) and I’m still hungry. I’ve experienced this before which is why I feel afraid of eating this way and feel like I have to fill up on salad and apples or I’ll gain weight instead of lose weight. Even after almost 1500 calories for breakfast with 200g (uncooked weight) of legumes I feel like I’m starving without fruit. I’ve been told that legumes are recommended for weight loss and for feeling satisfied so I don’t understand why this doesn’t apply to me.

Looks like I’ve finally had some success preventing a spike from breakfast. (Well sort of. See next note after 8pm re the spike several hours later.) So a ratio of 15 and pre-bolusing might be important.
Update at 4:20pm: But now I’m hypo. So from the graph what does it mean I should have done differently? I had Control-IQ off to prevent it from interfering with the data analysis. The 30-minute suspension was when I feared I had bolused too much with the new ratio.

Based on repeat observation, I think this spike is from the split peas, not from a lack of basal. But I’m not sure how to bolus for it because I don’t know yet how many hours it lasts and my pump doesn’t do more than 2 hours for an extended bolus.
Update: But only 10 minutes after I’ve given myself a correction bolus I’m rapidly dropping but what from??
I didn’t pre-bolus for the fruit tonight because I’d used a stronger ratio than normal for dinner and could see I was heading low.
Resuming the salad from breakfast that I didn’t finish
Bolusing 9.88 units when I’m already hypo just seems too scary
Was my mistake that caused my hypo my correction bolus?
I didn’t pre-bolus for dinner tonight because I was having a long phone call when I would normally pre-bolus and didn’t know when it would end.
I need to analyse why I spiked this morning whereas there were two walks recently where I didn’t spike after pre-workout drink. Did I do something different with Control-IQ those days?
Going for another walk to control my post-breakfast spike
Figure out why I went up to 6.8 this morning with no pre-workout drink or food and control IQ was on

The trouble with pre bolusing. I’d wanted to have some oranges now so I bolused but decided to wait for the insulin to take affect. While waiting to pass time I cooked some other food. Then I decided I might as well wait for that to finish cooking and eat that. But 45 mins pre-bolusing was too long and originally I’d wanted to just eat now.

Todo: use this to analyse how long my insulin lasts. It was 2 hours and 35 minutes ago that I last bolused and my BG is still falling even though I’ve had my basal suspended since I finished dinner. So it seems my bolus is still working.
I inserted a new Dexcom which might have contributed to the low readings.
Technically my fast was broken because of my hypo but I’m not counting hypo correction and my Macro Mike pre-workout drink as breaking my fasts.

I’m guessing this hypo was caused by leaving Control-IQ on while I was walking so my basal rate was probably too high whereas normally I have Control-IQ off while I walk.
Update: I’m no longer sure this was the cause because in the following days it seems I no longer need to bolus for my pre-workout drink or I’ve gone low. So on the 15/8 I tried an experiment leaving Control-IQ on while I walked but without bolusing for my pre-workout drink.
I didn’t eat much today and had a very late dinner because I was busy trying to get my dashboard upgraded for the session tomorrow.
It seems my strategy that was working well - bolusing at a ratio of 1:15 net carbs at the start of my legume veggie meal is too much insulin too soon if I have over 100g of (dry weight) legumes.

Strange that my pre-workout drink didn’t keep my from going hypo on my walk like it normally does and unlike yesterday I had Control-IQ off on my walk and suspended for the whole walk whereas normally I only need to suspend it for 30 minutes on my walk. Maybe it was because I only started drinking it during my walk rather than having it beforehand.
I suppose the reason for this hypo was because I left my caravan because of roadwork noise and only brought my salad with me so I didn’t have my usual fruit after it.

I had a big meal of fruit here, without even any veggies with the fruit and BG was great afterwards which is a huge improvement. I just used my ratio of 1:15 net carbs (no pre-bolusing either) and then suspended my insulin for a long time after eating. Todo: take note of how long I had my insulin suspended for to calculate how long my insulin lasts for, because my BG was just above 4 even after my insulin had been suspended a long time so obviously my bolus was still working.

So I may be over-correcting my usual BG spikes by bolusing too much lately but since before it seemed like I couldn’t even eat low GI fruit without spiking out of control I’m trying to test and gain confidence that I can actually eat foods like potatoes and other fruits instead of feeling like I have to avoid them like I was led to believe.
Feeling tired and thirsty, hence the extra pre-workout drink today. Noise has been affecting my sleep lately and today is very noisy. (Noise has a huge impact on me.)

It’s interesting I tried not bolusing for my pre-workout drinks today and so far I haven’t spiked whereas normally I need to bolus for them. It would be interesting to see if Control-IQ increased my basal after I had them.
I also experimented with leaving Control-IQ on while I walked today since I’m thinking a few days ago I might’ve gone low not because of Control-IQ but from bolusing for my pre-workout drink.
I got busy after my fruit meal and didn’t suspend my insulin soon enough afterwards.

I didn’t end up eating as much watermelon as I bolused for.
Lesson: bolusing for 1/4 watermelon especially after I’ve just eaten the first 1/4 of it is not the same as bolusing for an orange where I am not likely to have trouble finishing it. If unsure how much I will eat don’t bolus for the whole thing. 
Another lesson: I would have been better of cutting the watermelon off the rind before weighing and bolusing because the weight of the rind is a high percentage of the total weight so would lead to inaccurate bolusing.
I had the flavoured creatine today to compare my BG response to the unflavoured creatine yesterday.

Another hypo after watermelon and this time I can’t blame it on not finishing what I bolused for. This time I weighed just what I was going to eat without the rind before bolusing. I didn’t go for a walk afterwards but I had my insulin suspended the whole time so it seems my ratio of 1 unit to 15g net carbs is just too strong.
Trying a new ratio of 1 unit to 18g net carbs for this meal
Here’s another example of a split peas BG spike
I tried my gym session without bolusing for my pre-workout today. Normally I’ve been going high even after bolusing. I did do a correction bolus during my gym session though.
This seems a big spike from having 210g of raw carrots without bolusing.

10 reps x 12 chinups 
20 reps x 3 dips
All level 47kg assistance

workouts.name: Stationary Bike
workouts.notes: The first 30 mins was gentle level 1 as a recovery from the elliptical as well as because I was making notes while listening to the Mastering Diabetes University. After that I did level 2 around 90 RPM around 120bpm.

workouts.name: Elliptical
workouts.notes: I tried the one furthest on the right this time rather than my usual one that’s second from the left. This one had a flexible stride length.

workouts.name: Walking
workouts.notes: A slow pace with lots of pauses because I was busy making notes while listening to Mastering Diabetes content.

workouts.name: Walking
workouts.notes: Interesting Macro Mike pre workout drink didn’t prevent me going hypo on my walk. I wonder if my walk was too far after the drink and maybe Control-IQ fully countered the spike affect of the drink before my walk.
It was raining so I didn’t walk as long as other days.
workouts.name: Walking
Elliptical
workouts.notes: The one on the right which feels harder

workouts.name: Chin-up/Dip Station
workouts.notes: My workout is feeling harder today and not so good. Maybe because I was heavier when I weighed myself this morning.

workouts.name: Other Weight Machines
workouts.notes: Even the non-bodyweight exercises felt significantly harder today and I had to do less weight and reps, like I’ve just gotten weaker and my body isn’t feeling good training today.

workouts.name: Stationary Bike
workouts.notes: Very interesting. Even level 1 felt difficult at first like something was wrong but after about 18 minutes I started to feel better. (Although my heart rate still seemed higher than previously for level 1.) So I’m thinking maybe my mistake today was starting with the weights machines with only a brief warm up on the elliptical whereas normally I do cardio for much longer before the more intense exercises. After 2 weeks without the gym my body might have needed something gentle to start functioning again. My period is also trying to start which could be a factor too.

workouts.name: Elliptical
workouts.notes: Heart rate wasn’t being recorded so I started a new recording.

workouts.name: Elliptical
workouts.notes: The second from the left - the easier machine. On only level 1 but it seems my theory might be right because this felt okay.
